    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2546108713" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2546108713" />
    <a title="Onaiza Khan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41525544-onaiza-khan"><img alt="Onaiza Khan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1458226061p2/41525544.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2546108713?book_show_action=true">Nov 26, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Onaiza Khan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Onaiza Khan" href="/user/show/41525544-onaiza-khan">Onaiza Khan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41525544-onaiza-khan?shelf=indian-writings">indian-writings</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41525544-onaiza-khan?shelf=novels">novels</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2546108713" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3650756556709299084">Finishing this book feels like a milestone in life. First of all, because it is enormous and secondly because I&apos;ve learnt a lot from it. I think the plot design is impressive. Everything happens just when it should in the story. And although there are multiple storylines at work, they do not create any confusion. The story is well laid out, especially the political scenario of Post-Independence India. The end is satisfying and justified. <br/><br/>But there is too much I do not like. Seth begins his book </span>
  <span id="freeText3650756556709299084" style="display:none">Finishing this book feels like a milestone in life. First of all, because it is enormous and secondly because I've learnt a lot from it. I think the plot design is impressive. Everything happens just when it should in the story. And although there are multiple storylines at work, they do not create any confusion. The story is well laid out, especially the political scenario of Post-Independence India. The end is satisfying and justified. <br /><br />But there is too much I do not like. Seth begins his book with the quote "the secret of being a bore is to tell everything" by Voltaire. It is ironic that Seth himself is trying to tell everything in his book. The book has too much information. It is full of cultural references and colloquialisms that are bland and unnecessary. Being an Indian, I understand too well the cultural and political peculiarities. But I wouldn't expect a non-Indian reader to be able to grasp it all. In his effort to produce a fast-paced novel, Seth has left out even the important details without which much of it doesn't make sense. <br /><br />Although this book did remind me of a novel by Tolstoy, Seth's work seemed a cheap imitation of it instead of an interesting reminder. The characters are under-developed, naive and very typical. Even though they have elaborate back-stories, they still come out as one-dimensional and shallow. They don't have their own voices. There is only one voice, Seth's. <br /><br />Seth also fails at portraying emotions. For example in an emotionally charged scene when a younger brother tells his elder brother about being psychologically tortured at his school, the elder brother replies thus about the school, "the food was bad, the omelletes were like lizard's corpses...". Seth has gone just too far to present a sense of humour. But perhaps like most people, he doesn't know the right time to do it. <br /><br />And the dialogues, well they were unbelievably bad. Seth is continuously showing off his knowledge through his characters. Even though everything is well researched, there is just too much unnecessary information and these gory details pop out all too suddenly and out of context. For example, he throws around words like laparotomy without explanation and uselessly, whereas fails to use simple words in an intelligent manner. I'd like to quote some of the dialogues to draw a better picture here. <br /><br />"He stared at him in a hunted manner and turned away"<br /><br />"He fell into Pran's embrace and kept making these terrible animal sounds of grief"<br /><br />"Horrible retching sounds were coming from her throat"<br /><br />He also uses an enormous number of (horrid) couplets and rhymes of his own creation obviously (more show-off) which makes it hard to take the book seriously. I find the writing extremely weak and unsuitable (pun intended). I think this book is a huge disappointment and wouldn't recommend it to anyone. But on the plus side, I've learnt a lot about writing. A lot of these writing crimes I've been guilty of making myself and would try my best to avoid in the future.<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3650756556709299084" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


