    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3321717506" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3321717506" />
    <a title="Teenu Vijayan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/62769317-teenu-vijayan"><img alt="Teenu Vijayan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1600415403p2/62769317.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3321717506?book_show_action=true">Jun 12, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Teenu Vijayan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Teenu Vijayan" href="/user/show/62769317-teenu-vijayan">Teenu Vijayan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3321717506" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17042794070658898746">4.25 for the story, rest for me for finishing this ;)<br/>Lot of thoughts and ramblings ahead.<br/>What a book!! Had decoded the book in 6 parts on my Bookstagram, posting it here too.<br/>Post 1/6<br/>Today&apos;s post will be my views on the author- the fabulous Mr Vikram Seth.<br/>His name is something I remember listening to while growing up, more than in literary context it was for the general knowledge stuff that I learnt/read about him and this book. Picking up such a huge book is definitely intimidating and only thro</span>
  <span id="freeText17042794070658898746" style="display:none">4.25 for the story, rest for me for finishing this ;)<br />Lot of thoughts and ramblings ahead.<br />What a book!! Had decoded the book in 6 parts on my Bookstagram, posting it here too.<br />Post 1/6<br />Today's post will be my views on the author- the fabulous Mr Vikram Seth.<br />His name is something I remember listening to while growing up, more than in literary context it was for the general knowledge stuff that I learnt/read about him and this book. Picking up such a huge book is definitely intimidating and only through reliable friends who read and raved about this books did I muster up enough courage to give it a try.<br />The very first scene of the book captivated me, an elaborate wedding, a match making in process and odd ball relatives mushrooming across the pages. I was sucked inside the pages before even I knew it.<br />Writing is difficult.<br />Writing a family saga is more difficult.<br />Writing a family saga with 100 plus characters, back stories, character arcs, wavering locations, weaving in politics, religion and a million other things in between is definitely not easy.<br />But when you read, he makes it all look so simple, he never lets you feel that you are reading something so complex, intricate and soulful. The journey is slow and steady with the author guiding you throughout. The characters grow on you, you live and breath with them knowingly or unknowingly. That's the beauty of the writing in this book. The fictional world and reality merges so seamlessly that you are transported to the post independence India taking her baby steps into being a new country.<br />Another thing that I want to touch on is the amount of deep research he has painful taken to explain certain things. Whether it's the political climate, religious tensions, social behaviour, functioning of factories, oils, tannery, bookstores, parties or even child birth- nothing is off the mark. And that's a commendable job in itself!!<br /><br />Part 2/6 <br />Today's post will be of the geographical setting and communication amongst the characters of this book.<br />The heart of this spatial story is set in the mystical city of Brahmapur which adds that extra charm to everything.<br />Even though it's a fictional city, as the story unfolds you can visualize the serene banks of Ganga, the majestic Barasat Mahal, the courtesan houses, the religious places, prem niwas and Nawab Sahib's palace.<br />The strong atmospheric feeling while reading is almost like being wrapped in a warm blanket. To anyone who has read the book, if I say Barasat Mahal then the boat ride will materialize in front of your eyes.<br />Prem Niwas and the magical garden, it reminded me of Lal Bagh's flower show. Saaeda Begum's residence has half the secrets hidden amongst all the glittery sheen.<br />The other cities that play a part in the narration are few known ones. The most important one though is Calcutta with her jazz and dazz, heritage, howrah, culture, parties and a sense of liberation that is so infectious. Was pleasantly surprised with how modern the society of 1950's looked in the book. <br />Next is Delhi and Kanpur where transient decisions happen and they provide those perfect stops for the story to proceed. <br />Add in train journeys and frantic telephones, telegrams and soulful letter writing, the old world habits are something that makes you miss a time that you weren't even a part of.<br />I have always been a sucker for letters and have innumerable memories of train journeys as a kid, both these things felt so real to me. <br />In today's world when everything and everyone is a click away, it's almost wistful to want to have such experiences.<br /><br />Post 3/6 <br />Presenting the leading men of this book.<br />1. Kabir Durrani - He came like a fresh breath of air and swept me along the course of the book. A guy who reads, plays cricket , takes you on romantic dates (since I don't want to be a spoil sport won't go into details) is definitely getting brownie points from me. But behind the dreamy looks and romantic gestures, Kabir was a guy who just wanted to be loved. His backstory makes you want to pull him from his despair and spread some happiness in his life. <br />2. Amit Chatterjee- Amit the NRI poet is all things classy and charm. He brought a sense of calmness to the family. He was never shy of his feelings nor was too impulsive with them. He was meticulous in everything he did and chapter 13 was so much special because of his smart brains. I always like intelligent men, doesn't hurt that he loved Jane Austen a little much too. I loved reading about him and his quirks. <br />3. Haresh Khanna- He's the most rustic out of the lot. He came nursing a broken heart, sorrow sitting on his mantel, desi to the core with an unabashed level of confidence that grows on you eventually. Paan chewing London return boy won me over with his dedication. His sheer will to get things done. He might not be refined like the other two but he makes a place in your heart unknowingly before you realize it.<br /><br />Now I can't dwell more in details but it was a guessing game for me and I kept changing my answers periodically 😂😬 as mentioned before, the communication of all three men are as unique as their personality. Personally I loved Amit's letter the most (THE ONE).<br />It's interesting how the men come to Lata's life. She meets Kabir in Brahmapur, unknowingly Haresh see's her on the train station where she is enroute to meet Amit. I felt the symbolism by the author makes so much more sense when you finish the book.<br />The little details make me smile when I think about the book. Things that could turn cringey are handled with an undeniable smoothness by Mr Seth (hint: cricket stadium) . Read the book to know more 😉<br />Swipe to see the men whom I picturized while reading the book. <br />@namitdas is the perfect casting for Haresh 😍😍<br /><br /> Post 4/6 of #DecodingASuitableboy <br />Today I want to talk about "bonds"<br />When a story has these many characters, the connecting thread is definitely the bonds they form- however fleeting - over the course of events.<br />Maan the reckless jovial boy and Firoz the sophisticated mature have a bond that is definitely thicker than blood relations. We see their friendship develop and blossom into a strong love that withstood many storms. From playing to having each others back through thick and thin, they proved that you needn't share blood to be brothers.<br />Not to left beyond is their fathers, Mahesh Kapoor- Nawab Sahib are what they call chalk and cheese. But despite the superficial difference of religion, political beliefs, they have this unsaid friendship has the sense of understanding where one look can convey the plethora of emotions.<br />One of my favourite scenes of the book is the court scene where all the four characters showcased what true friendship means. <br />I want to talk a little about the Chatterjee clan too, they are the most modern one's out of the lot. The parents have let the children forge a path for themselves, even though they might not be on the same page, but they aren't overbearing even a bit. The elder son decides to ditch law and focus on a writing and indulges in the luxury of the process, the fruits aren't seen yet, but they let him do it. Another one is soul seeking across the country and despite his eccentric nature, the family has no judgements. The two girls- Meenakshi might be a bitch but she is that spoilt rich brat. The ease with which the family has handled the never ending suitor's for Kuku is commendable and respecting her choice too. My favourite moment was how the brothers stepped up to handle the crisis of their younger brother. Shows how despite seeming aloof, when the need arises they had each others back.<br />There are few more that I loved, Kabir's broken family trying to clutch onto few happy memories of their mother, Rasheed enchained in a loveless marriage trying to honour his family's wishes and at the same time wanting to respect the people who were important to his upbringing.<br /><br />Post 5/6 <br />We are almost at the end of my ramblings, I'm honestly thankful for the kind response from you all 🥰<br />Today I'll be taking about the "couples" that these pages hold. <br />Right from the beginning we know it's a quest for finding a suitable boy for Lata. But despite her being the protagonist of this saga, she barely proves to be an interesting character in my opinion. I wish she had more guts or clarity regarding her muddled and fleeting emotions. I can go on a full fledged rant but since that's not today's agenda, I will move onto the topic at hand.<br />The first chapter shows us the most sorted, happy and mutually amiable couple of the entire book- Pran and Savita. Despite lacking what some might call a whirlwind romance or yearning for each other, this couple showed what companionship was all about. Adjusting to each others family and life in general was as easy for them as easily they grew fond of the other person. The term having each others back through thick and thin was seen here and I shed couple of years for them. The scene in hospital where fate's humdrum hung mercilessly over their future, they showed how one can win over adverse events by being themselves and maybe with a splash of humour. <br />A sharp contrast in the difference of feelings/love is seen during the Barasat Mahal lake-date (as I would like to call it), we see two couple who embark on this journey and both their perspective and emotions are stark opposite of the other (L-K and P-S for those who have read the book). Shows how a mature relation grows over time.<br />These two honestly made arranged marriage seem so enjoyable.Taking a sharp contrast we have the despicable couple of Arun and Meenakshi. Two spoilt brats who are snooty, arrogant and selfish to the core.They balance their negative traits with each other too. Arun still showed some human ways, Meenakshi is the odd one from the entire clan.We also see the infatuated Maan spend a good amount of his time with Saaeda Begum and though I have my reservation about if this relationship was worth it, somewhere they did have a sort of hold on each others life. <br /><br />Post 6/6 <br />Today's post is an ode to Mr Seth.<br />People who have read the book, you can notice an Easter egg here 🤭 my small tribute to Amit who won me over in Chapter 13 with his wordplay. I am no poet so please forgive me for this silly scramble. Here it goes-<br />Vagabound heart, bequeathed by the cross roads winding up slowly<br />Ineffable they said, this tale of folly<br />Knew no one what to expect if we are to admit it wholly<br />Rendering the unknown, rare will the times we rejoiced oh so holy!<br />Adore, admire and sigh we did, the pages entwined in a knot so fully <br />Magic is what you fabricated, the world created, cementing the aura so brightly<br />Spell-bound we sat, holding onto the precious words intently<br />Enabling us to tread on this path, walking into the glitch in the matrix cautiously<br />Thank you the guiding us so effortlessly<br />Having lived in this beautiful world will be cherished oh so fondly <br />~<br />Just wanted to say a small thanks for all the love for this decoding series, you guys surprise me with your kindness ❤️<br />There is still a lot unsaid that's left, but I'm stopping here. <br />These characters will be with me for a long time, that much I know. One book hangover that I shall never regret, make time for this one people. This is a ride that you shouldn't miss.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17042794070658898746" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


